proofs.proof_tex:
\begin{proof}
Fix $P\in\mathcal P_\epsilon$. First let $Q\in\mathfrak Q_\epsilon(P)$ and write $p_{m\ell}=q_s$, which is possible for a unique $s$ because the cutpoints are strictly ordered and, on the domain $\mathcal P_\epsilon$, every propensity is a represented cutpoint. Uniformity of $U$ gives
\[
\sum_{i,j}r^Q_{mkij}=Q(U\in I_k\mid X=x_m)=\lambda_k.
\tag{1}
\]
For a treated factual cell, consistency, threshold selection, conditional IV exogeneity, and the absence of atoms of a uniform $U$ at the cutpoints imply
\begin{align*}
b_{1\ell hm}
&=Q(Y=y_h,D=1\mid Z=z_\ell,X=x_m)\\
&=Q(Y(1)=y_h,U\le q_s\mid X=x_m)\\
&=\sum_{k=1}^{s}\sum_{i=1}^Jr^Q_{mkih}
=\sum_{k:q_k\le p_{m\ell}}\sum_{i=1}^Jr^Q_{mkih}.
\tag{2}
\end{align*}
Likewise, for an untreated cell,
\begin{align*}
b_{0\ell hm}
&=Q(Y(0)=y_h,U>q_s\mid X=x_m)\\
&=\sum_{k=s+1}^{K}\sum_{j=1}^Jr^Q_{mkhj}
=\sum_{k:q_{k-1}\ge p_{m\ell}}\sum_{j=1}^Jr^Q_{mkhj}.
\tag{3}
\end{align*}
Thus $A_m^Pr^Q=b_m$ for every $m$. The two rank-shape assumptions give exactly the two displayed systems of rank inequalities in $\mathcal R_\infty(P)$, while the association-floor assumption gives $S(r^Q)\ge\kappa_0-\epsilon$. Together with (1)--(3) and nonnegativity, this proves $r^Q\in\mathcal R_\epsilon(P)$. Moreover, conditioning on $X$ and partitioning by $(I_k,Y(0),Y(1))$ yields
\begin{align*}
\delta_Q
&=\sum_{m=1}^M\alpha_m\sum_{k=1}^K\sum_{i,j=1}^J
(\omega_k^+-\omega_k^-)1\{a\le y_j-y_i\le b\}
Q(U\in I_k,Y(0)=y_i,Y(1)=y_j\mid X=x_m)\\
&=\sum_{m,k,i,j}\alpha_md_kc_{ij}r^Q_{mkij}=\Delta(r^Q).
\tag{4}
\end{align*}

Conversely, fix $r\in\mathcal R_\epsilon(P)$. Construct a law as follows. Draw $X=x_m$ with probability $\alpha_m$. Conditional on $X=x_m$, draw a discrete label $(K^*,I^*,J^*)=(k,i,j)$ with probability $r_{mkij}$. Conditional on that label, draw $U$ uniformly on $I_k$ (endpoint conventions are immaterial because this distribution is atomless), and set $Y(0)=y_i$, $Y(1)=y_j$. Independently of $(K^*,I^*,J^*,U)$ given $X=x_m$, draw $Z=z_\ell$ with probability $\pi_{\ell m}$. Finally set
\[D=1\{U\le p_{m\ell}\}\quad\text{on }\{Z=z_\ell,X=x_m\},\qquad
Y=DY(1)+(1-D)Y(0).\tag{5}
\]
The cell-mass equations in $\mathcal R_\infty(P)$ imply that the conditional density of $U$ on each $I_k$ is $\lambda_k/\lambda_k=1$; hence $U\mid X=x_m$ is uniform on $[0,1]$. The construction makes $(Y(0),Y(1),U)\perp Z\mid X$ and enforces consistency and threshold selection. By the same calculation as (2)--(3), now read from right to left, the conditional probabilities of $(Y,D)$ given $(Z,X)$ equal the cells $b_{d\ell hm}$. Since the constructed $(X,Z)$ marginal is $\alpha_m\pi_{\ell m}$, its observed marginal is exactly $P$. Its response array is $r$ by construction; therefore its rank-shape and association restrictions follow from $r\in\mathcal R_\epsilon(P)$. Thus the constructed law belongs to $\mathfrak Q_\epsilon(P)$ and has $r^Q=r$. Equation (4) also applies to it.
\end{proof}

theorem.proof_tex:
\begin{proof}
Because $\mathcal R_\epsilon(P)$ is a nonempty closed subset of the bounded product of simplices determined by $\sum_{i,j}r_{mkij}=\lambda_k$, it is compact. It is convex because all its restrictions are linear. Hence its image under the linear map $\Delta$ is a compact convex subset of $\mathbb R$, and therefore is the interval between its attained minimum and maximum. By lem:factual-map-and-pasting, every compatible structural law maps to its response array without changing the target, and every feasible response array is pasted into a compatible structural law. Consequently
\[
\operatorname{Id}^{\epsilon}_P(\delta_Q)
=\{\Delta(r):r\in\mathcal R_\epsilon(P)\}
=[\delta_L(P,\epsilon),\delta_U(P,\epsilon)].
\tag{1}
\]
This proves sharpness, including attainment of every interior point (equivalently, take convex combinations of endpoint arrays and paste the resulting array).

Now fix $P$ satisfying the second sentence of the theorem. Positivity, overlap, and cutpoint saturation do not depend on $e$. Put $R=\mathcal R_\infty(P)$ and $s_-=\overline S_-(P)$. The set $R$ is a nonempty compact polytope, and the assumed nonemptiness of $R^- =\{r\in R:\Delta(r)\le0\}$ makes $s_-$ finite and attained. For every $e\ge0$,
\begin{align*}
P\in\mathcal P_e\text{ and }\delta_L(P,e)\le0
&\Longleftrightarrow \exists r\in R:\ S(r)\ge\kappa_0-e,\ \Delta(r)\le0\\
&\Longleftrightarrow s_-\ge\kappa_0-e.
\tag{2}
\end{align*}
The first equivalence is the definition of the feasible domain and the attained minimum; the second is the definition and attainment of $s_-$. Thus the set in def:sign-flip-radius is exactly
\[
\{e\ge0:e\ge\kappa_0-s_-\},
\tag{3}
\]
whose infimum is $(\kappa_0-s_-)_+$. This proves the radius formula.

For the shape of the path, if $e_2\ge e_1$ then $\mathcal R_{e_1}(P)\subseteq\mathcal R_{e_2}(P)$, so minimization gives $\delta_L(P,e_2)\le\delta_L(P,e_1)$. Write the association constraint as $\kappa_0-e-S(r)\le0$. Finite-dimensional LP strong duality gives the one-multiplier representation
\[
\delta_L(P,e)=\sup_{\mu\ge0}
\left[\mu(\kappa_0-e)+\min_{r\in R}
\{\Delta(r)-\mu S(r)\}\right].
\tag{4}
\]
For each $\mu$, the displayed expression is affine in $e$ with slope $-\mu$; its supremum is therefore convex. Alternatively, enumerating the finitely many bases of the LP shows directly that on its feasible domain the value is piecewise affine and finite. The feasible domain itself is the closed ray $E_P=\{e\ge0:\max_{r\in R}S(r)\ge\kappa_0-e\}$, so a finite convex piecewise-affine function is continuous relative to $E_P$. If $\mu_e$ is the unique optimal association multiplier at a relative-interior point, (4) and the finite-basis value calculus imply that the subdifferential is the singleton $\{-\mu_e\}$; hence $\delta_L'(P,e)=-\mu_e$.

Finally suppose the additional strict-sign conditions hold. Because $P\in\mathcal P_0$, all $e\ge0$ are feasible. Formula (2) and $s_-<\kappa_0$ show that no $r\in\mathcal R_e(P)$ can have $\Delta(r)\le0$ when $e<\kappa_0-s_-=\epsilon^\dagger(P)$. Compactness then strengthens the pointwise inequality to $\delta_L(P,e)>0$. At $e=\epsilon^\dagger(P)$, an optimizer $r^-\in R^-$ of $S$ satisfies $S(r^-)=s_-=\kappa_0-e$ and $\Delta(r^-)\le0$, so it is feasible and $\delta_L(P,e)\le0$. Choose also $r^{<}\in R$ with $\Delta(r^{<})<0$. For any $e>\epsilon^\dagger(P)$ and sufficiently small $\tau\in(0,1)$,
\[
r_\tau=(1-\tau)r^-+\tau r^{<}
\quad\text{satisfies}\quad
S(r_\tau)>\kappa_0-e,\qquad \Delta(r_\tau)<0.
\tag{5}
\]
Thus $r_\tau\in\mathcal R_e(P)$, and lem:factual-map-and-pasting supplies $Q_e\in\mathfrak Q_e(P)$ with $\delta_{Q_e}=\Delta(r_\tau)<0$.
\end{proof}

added_lemmas.proof_tex:
\begin{proof}
Introduce a nonnegative slack for $g^Tt\le0$ and split each free equality-dual coordinate into positive and negative parts. Strong duality gives
\[
V(\theta)=\min_{(y,\nu)\in\mathcal D}y^T\theta,
\qquad
\mathcal D=\{(y,\nu):B^Ty+\nu g\ge s,\nu\ge0\}.
\tag{1}
\]
The feasible set $\mathcal D$ is a fixed polyhedron. A standard-form basis is a choice of finitely many columns; hence only finitely many basic dual solutions can determine a finite optimum on the relative interior of the primal feasible right-hand-side domain. Thus, locally on that domain, $V$ is the minimum of finitely many affine maps $\theta\mapsto y_a^T\theta$. This proves concavity, continuity, and piecewise affinity. For any $h_n\to h$ and $t_n\downarrow0$, only dual bases optimal at $\theta$ can remain optimal along $\theta+t_nh_n$; direct subtraction in (1) then yields
\[
\lim_n\frac{V(\theta+t_nh_n)-V(\theta)}{t_n}
=\min_{(y,\nu)\in\mathcal D^*(\theta)}y^Th.
\tag{2}
\]
This is Hadamard directional differentiability. If a unique nonsingular strictly complementary basis is optimal, its reduced costs and positive basic coordinates remain strict under small right-hand-side perturbations. The same basis is therefore uniquely optimal nearby, so $V$ is affine with gradient $y$. Reversing max to min changes the lower envelope in (1) to an upper envelope. If a scalar relaxation enters its right-hand side with coefficient $-1$, the active affine piece has slope minus the corresponding nonnegative dual multiplier; uniqueness makes the subdifferential a singleton and hence gives ordinary differentiability.
\end{proof}
